article.headline: Missouri 71, Texas Tech 58
article.story: COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- Mike Anderson got the best of Bobby Knight, earning the biggest victory of his first season at Missouri. Stefhon Hannah led a balanced attack with 15 points and four assists and the Tigers' all-court pressure knocked short-handed Texas Tech out of its rhythm in a 71-58 victory on Saturday. "It was Missouri vs. Texas Tech, that's how I see it," Anderson said. "You want to defend your home turf and we hadn't played well the previous two games in conference play. I thought it was due time." Missouri blew a 16-point lead in its conference opener against Iowa State and trailed by 16 before losing by four to Kansas State on Jan. 13. The Tigers were in control most of the way against Texas Tech, without injured starters Charlie Burgess and Jon Plefka. Marshall Brown and Leo Lyons each had 11 points for Missouri (13-6, 2-4 Big 12), which won its second straight conference game after an 0-4 start. Anderson matched wits against Knight for the first time in a game that drew 15,061, Missouri's first sellout of the season. "I'll tell you what, atmosphere makes a big difference," Anderson said. "You saw our guys take it up to another level." Missouri beat Texas Tech for the first time in four meetings while topping its season victory total from last season's 12-16 finish. The Tigers beat a team that entered tied for first place in the conference. "We knew they were a really good team, they were No. 1 in the league, and that always gives you something to shoot for," Brown said. "We just felt really confident going into the game that we were going to get a win." Martin Zeno had 14 points and Jarrius Jackson 12 for Texas Tech (15-6, 4-2), which failed to build on momentum created by victories over No. 8 Kansas and No. 6 Texas A&M in its previous two games -- both at home. The Red Raiders committed 15 turnovers and got outrebounded 34-29 while falling to 1-2 on the road in conference play. Plefka was sidelined by a leg injury Knight said was sustained against Texas A&M on Wednesday and Burgess, who averages 9.9 points, sprained an ankle when he slipped on a basketball during the team's shootaround earlier in the day. Knight said Plefka will undergo an MRI exam for an injury he described as a "tear" and that Burgess could "barely walk" at game time. To Knight, the problem against Missouri was manpower rather than overconfidence from the recent successes. "Son, we just got beat," Knight said to a Missouri student reporter. "We had two guys that didn't play that have been instrumental in our team all year. There wasn't any letdown." Texas Tech missed its first 10 shots of the second half and had five turnovers while Missouri ran off 10 straight points for a 51-35 lead with 13 minutes to go. The Red Raiders were scoreless in the half until Decensae White connected from inside with 10:23 left. Knight said if he knew why "I'd be talking to George Bush today and helping him instead of being here." "We just really couldn't get the game into a situation at any time where we were really threatening. The best chance we had was at the start of the second half and we didn't get anything done." Missouri led by at least 12 points the rest of the way and Hannah's 3-pointer provided a 17-point cushion at 63-46 with 6:18 to go. Texas Tech also was cold to start the game, but not to that extent, although the Red Raiders never led. Brown hit two 3-pointers in the opening minute for a quick 6-0 Missouri lead, but then committed two quick fouls in a span of 17 seconds and sat down for the remainder of the half with 15:44 to go. His teammates picked up the slack, and successive 3-pointers in an 11-second span by Jason Horton with the shot clock near zero and Matt Lawrence off a turnover put the Tigers ahead 37-24 with 4:14 to go. Texas Tech scored the last six points, two of the baskets coming off steals, to shave the deficit to six at the half. One of the baskets came from Jackson, who had seven points in the half after being held scoreless the first 9 1/2 minutes.
